{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17513390","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17513390"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:09:39+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:09:39+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12107"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12107","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12107"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.2,0.18,0.14,0.44,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4652"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78153"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4652","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4652"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12107"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63575"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"29"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"7005"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7087"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7192"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26777"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39832"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78153","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78153"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 40-year-old woman presents to the clinic with complaints of progressive muscle weakness and cold intolerance. Physical examination reveals enlargement of her thyroid gland, which is rubbery in consistency. No lymphadenopathy is found. Laboratory evaluation finds decreased serum levels of both free triiodothyronine (fT3) and free thyroxine (fT4), but serum levels of thyroid-stimulating hormone (TSH) are increased. No thyroid-stimulating immunoglobulins are identified in the serum, but thyroidal peroxidase autoantibodies are present.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following histologic finding is most likely to be present?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Diffuse fibrous deposition between atrophic follicles","Follicular cell hyperplasia with scalloping of colloid","Granulomatous inflammation with multinucleated giant cells","Lymphoid infiltrate with scattered Hurthle cells","Parafollicular hyperplasia with deposition of amyloid"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis presentation is suggestive of Hashimoto thyroiditis, which is an autoimmune disease that destroys thyroid cells by cell and antibody-mediated immune processes. These patients may have a period of hyperthyroidism before the thyroid \u0027burns out\u0027 and the patient becomes hypothyroid.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe pathology of the disease involves the formation of antithyroid antibodies that attack the thyroid tissue, causing progressive fibrosis. It is characterized histologically by an intense \u003Cstrong\u003Elymphoplasmacytic infiltrate, \u003C/strong\u003Ewith the formation of lymphoid follicles and germinal centers. This produces destruction and atrophy of the follicles and transforms the thyroid follicular cells into acidophilic cells. There are many different names for these cells, including oxyphilic cells, oncocytes, and H\u00fcrthle cells. H\u00fcrthle cells arise from the follicular epithelium. Key features of these oncocytic cells include a granular cytoplasm that stains eosinophilic and a vesicular nucleus with a large nucleolus. Correlation with the presence of thyroid autoantibodies, namely anti-TPO and anti-Tg, is helpful in confirming the diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Hashimoto thyroiditis is part of the spectrum of autoimmune thyroid diseases and is characterized by the destruction of thyroid cells by various cell- and antibody-mediated immune processes.","It is characterised by extensive lymphocytic infiltrate with the germinal center formation."],"references":["Omidan N, Zahir ST, Fateh A. Cytological and Pathological Evaluation of Hashimoto\u0027s Thyroiditis. Maedica (Bucur). 2019 Jun;14(2):98-103. doi: 10.26574/maedica.2019.14.2.98. PMID: 31523288; PMCID: PMC6709394. Available from: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC6709394/","Mincer DL, Jialal I. Hashimoto Thyroiditis. 2023 Jul 29. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan\u2013. PMID: 29083758. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/29083758/","Li Y, Zhou G, Ozaki T, Nishihara E, Matsuzuka F, Bai Y, Liu Z, Taniguchi E, Miyauchi A, Kakudo K. Distinct histopathological features of Hashimoto\u0027s thyroiditis with respect to IgG4-related disease. Mod Pathol. 2012 Aug;25(8):1086-97. doi: 10.1038/modpathol.2012.68. Epub 2012 May 4. PMID: 22555173. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/22555173/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63575"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12107"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63575","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63575"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-09T14:50:11+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-09T14:51:06+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4652"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78153"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"